a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tregoz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish (Cornwall and Devon): habitational name from Treago in Crantock (Cornwall). The placename derives from Middle Cornish <i>tre</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + uncertain final element.","Altered form of French   Tricot   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname. It was reportedly brought to North America from England. Today it is found mainly in PA and OH. Compare   Trago  .","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Tricot","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French:","nickname from a diminutive of <i>trique</i> ‘cudgel’."]},{"name":"Trago","meanings":["Variant of   Trego  , a surname of Cornish and French origin. In the US, it is found mainly in PA and OH."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Tregoz was born about 1304, in Wymondham, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir John de Toly."},"et":{"about 1304–":"umbes 1304–Surnud","1301–1352":"1301–1352","1325–1392":"1325–1392","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1301":"1301","about 1304":"umbes 1304","1352":"1352","1392":"1392","Wymondham, Leicestershire, England":"Wymondham, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1304–":"noin 1304–Kuollut","1301–1352":"1301–1352","1325–1392":"1325–1392","1304–Female":"1304–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1301":"1301","about 1304":"noin 1304","1352":"1352","1392":"1392","Wymondham, Leicestershire, England":"Wymondham, Leicestershire, England"},"fr":{"about 1304–":"environ 1304–Décédée","1301–1352":"1301–1352","1325–1392":"1325–1392","1304–Female":"1304–Décédée","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1301":"1301","about 1304":"environ 1304","1352":"1352","1392":"1392","Wymondham, Leicestershire, England":"Wymondham, Leicestershire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret de Tregoz est née environ 1304, à Wymondham, Leicestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Sir John de Toly."},"de":{"about 1304–":"um 1304–Verstorben","1301–1352":"1301–1352","1325–1392":"1325–1392","1304–Female":"1304–Verstorben","1304":"1304","1325":"1325","1301":"1301","about 1304":"um 1304","1352":"1352","1392":"1392","Wymondham, Leicestershire, England":"Wymondham, Leicestershire, England","lifeSummary":"Margaret de Tregoz wurde um 1304 in Wymondham, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdo